The Gores Holdings, Inc. Acquisition Of Hostess Is More Expensive Than It Looks - Hostess Brands, Inc. (NASDAQ:TWNK) | Seeking AlphaSign in / Join NowGOÂ»The Gores Holdings, Inc. Acquisition Of Hostess Is More Expensive Than It LooksOct. 3.16 | About: Hostess Brands, (TWNK) Investor Gator Alternative energy, industrials, long/short equity, special situationsSummaryThe Gores Holdings, Inc. (GRSH) acquisition of Hostess is complicated and deserves a close look at the mechanics.Correcting for a set of cherry-picked comparable companies moves the reference valuation range down from 13.4x EBITDA to between 9.2x EBITDA and 10.1x EBITDA.Including in the purchase price a tax savings sharing obligation estimated at $165M and a highly probably 2016 earn out adds 0.8x EBITDA to the acquisition price of Hostess.After these adjustments, Hostess appears to be valued at or above the top end of the comparable trading range at the current GRHS price of $10.80 per share.Note: while the current price of GRSH is $10.80, the company uses a reference price of $10.00 in its most recent September investor presentation. I use $10.00 per share from here on to maintain consistency across comparisons. Introduction As far as most special purpose acquisition company ("SPAC") transactions go, the Hostess acquisition by Gores Holdings (GRSH) looks like a winner. A proven brand, a proven management team staying on-board after the sale and an easy-to-understand story all suggest good things to come for those considering a long position. The transaction mechanics are complicated, though. So a further look at the purchase of Hostess by Gores Holdings makes sense as a matter of diligence and, in particular, to verify the sponsor's claim on page 20 of the most recent investor presentation that "Gore's acquisition of Hostess will occur at a meaningful discount to peers' TEV/EBITDA trading levels" Transaction Mechanics Before I could drill down on valuation, I wanted to understand better both a) the net impact of the changes in common stock and warrants arising from the transaction; and b) the cash and non-cash sources and uses required to complete the transaction An initial look through the supporting information in the investor presentation and press releases left me frustrated. While there was a lot of good information contained therein, I found it necessary to comb through the various merger filings to put together what I consider a complete look.
 Fully Diluted Ownership The presentation includes some essential information on capitalization, but it is far from complete. The dilutive impact of over 56M warrants is not accounted for and the sources and uses are not adequately detailed. Pulling together information from the company's periodic filings as well as the transaction filings allows for a more complete picture: 

 The presentation does a good job of providing the detailed shareholdings for the sponsors and seller post-transaction, indicating that Metropolous will own a very incentivizing 25.1%, Gores will retain 8% and original SPAC shareholders will retain 29% (down from 80%). But those ownership levels do not take into account potential impact from the exercise of the warrants and other dilutive events. The table above takes into account the potential dilution from the 56.5M outstanding warrants (exercisable for one-half share each) issued to the public and in connection with the private placement. Exercise of the warrants would take public shareholder ownership down nearly 18% from 28.9% to 23.8%. It's also worth noting the potential dilutive impact from another 8.25M shares to be issued if certain earn out targets are achieved is excluded from the table above. Sources and Uses Required to Complete the Transaction The pro forma valuation and sources and uses are also lacking some detail that would be very helpful to prospective investors. In particular I was curious as to the 'de-levering amount'. It turns out that embedded in that number is $40M of target cash that is hinted at but not clearly accounted for in the presentation. Again, going through the filings we can fill in some of those essential details: 


 Now that we've supplemented the investor presentation with some essential details from the filings on the mechanics of the transaction such as shareholding pre and post transaction and the specific cash and non-cash sources and uses, it's time to dig a little deeper on valuation. Valuation Hostess is an iconic brand with an emotional connection to U.S. consumers. However, it seems most of the company's products (Twinkies, cupcakes, extended shelf life bread) are on the very wrong side of a powerful secular trend toward fresh, local, healthy and organic eating. Hostess products will certainly maintain an esteemed place within the 'indulgent snacks' category, but once the accelerated growth from the company's re-introduction to the marketplace wears off this year, I am skeptical of long-term growth due to secular trends and general competition within the food category. As such, buying Hostess at a discount to peers, as the investor presentation claims it is being offered, is all the more important. Page 20 of the investor presentation shows a group of seven mid-cap food companies that seem to anchor the relative valuation and shows a median EV/2016E EBITDA multiple of 13.4x versus the presented Hostess multiple of 10.4x. Trading Comps Looking at the seven specific mid-cap trading comps selected by the company to justify the valuation versus the broader fifty or so diversified food companies of which they are a subset reveals a cherry-picked data set. 

 The seven companies chosen by the company to support the valuation are highlighted in yellow. You can see that while Hostess (represented by the box of Twinkies) is in the bottom 20%-25% by market cap at an estimated $1.3B, the company-selected comps are all substantially larger, with six of the seven being in the top half for market cap. Many of the company-chosen comps are broader and more diversified than Hostess. One comp, McCormick, is really in a different business altogether - spices.
 The impact of the cherry picking is made clear in the table below. It resulted in a much higher multiple for the comparable group. Since I don't have access to the forward EBITDA estimates used by the company in preparing the presentation, I used trailing EBITDA multiples for this exercise. This is reasonable in light of the steady growth of the sector and the higher accuracy from historical versus projected data. Since we're comparing the relative difference between big and small companies, whether we use historical or projected EBITDA does not matter because of the steady state nature of the industry. As the top part of the table below shows, the comparable multiple decreases significantly when a more appropriate group of comparables is chosen.  

 The seven larger, more diversified and sometimes altogether different comparable companies chosen by the company have a median market cap of $5B and a median EV/TTM EBITDA multiple 15.8x. Choosing a more appropriate comp group for Hostess, which is anticipated to have a $1.3B market cap when it debuts (according to the company's assumed price of $10.00 per share in the presentation), reduces the comp group multiple to:  12.3x EBITDA for all fifty food companies, including the largest one; or 10.1x EBITDA for a more appropriate comp group with market caps between $900M and $2B; or 9.2x EBITDA when an even more appropriate comp group with market caps between $900M and $2B is chosen  It's worth pausing here to note again that the presentation, in using the seven chosen mid-cap food companies, shows a median multiple of 13.4x, not the 15.8x I show above. That's because whereas I use trailing EBITDA, the presentation uses a more opaque estimated forward EBITDA. The critical point is that the *relative* difference in multiples between the large and small food companies is meaningful and completely changes the nature of the comparison. This would hold true whether trailing or forward numbers are used since the industry is characterized by mature, steady growth.
 Hostess Valuation There is a bit of work to be done on the Hostess multiple too. In looking at the Hostess multiple, I choose to use the company's 2016 estimated EBITDA instead of the trailing EBITDA as I have for the comps. Why? 2016 represents the first year of steady state operations for Hostess after significant, transformative changes and its subsequent re-introduction to the marketplace. Although it would help my argument to use a lower trailing EBITDA number, using forward EBITDA is actually a better apples-to-apples comparison versus the comp group. As the data at the bottom of the previous table shows, doing so results in a 10.5x EV/EBITDA multiple for Hostess assuming, as the company has done in its own presentation, a share price of $10.00 for GRSH. However, the presentation valuation excludes the obligation arising from a binding tax savings sharing agreement with the seller. While the exact amount of the obligation is unknown, the accountants estimate the liability at over $165M in the merger filings. Given the profitability of Hostess, it seems highly probable such payments will be made. In addition to the tax savings sharing obligation, the sellers are entitled to 8.25M additional shares via earn outs. The first of these, based on a 2016 EBITDA target of $225.4M also seems highly probable. Adding the additional cost of both of these obligations in moves the multiple from 10.5x to 11.3x (note, that excludes the additional 2017 and 2018 earnouts). Conclusion While the purchase of Hostess by Gores Holdings has several positive aspects to it, a closer look at the numbers reveals it appears to be coming to market at no discount. Whereas at a GRHS price per share of $10.00 Hostess will be valued at an EV/EBITDA multiple of between 10.5x and 11.3x, an appropriate set of food comps is currently trading at a multiple of between 9.2x and 10.1x EBITDA. Given that operational improvements will be difficult to obtain after the excellent restructuring work of the prior owners, and that the company's products likely face a stiff growth headwind from secular trends, the apparent lack of discount to trading peers is a red flag.

Disclosure: I/we have no positions in any stocks mentioned, and no plans to initiate any positions within the next 72 hours. 
